WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.833
‐ Your story shows

00:02.833 --> 00:04.292
that the highest levels
of the company

00:04.292 --> 00:07.500
knew exactly how dangerous
the drug was.

00:07.500 --> 00:08.875
‐ Okay, I'll testify.

00:08.875 --> 00:11.792
Please, I just need some Oxy.

00:11.792 --> 00:14.125
She's relapsing
from the stress.

00:14.125 --> 00:16.042
She can't testify.

00:16.042 --> 00:18.167
‐ No! No, Dad, please!

00:18.167 --> 00:19.958
‐...destroyed our damn family!

00:19.958 --> 00:22.708
‐ Please, Dad!
‐ Get your hands off of me!

00:23.750 --> 00:25.458
A shares have a majority

00:25.458 --> 00:26.792
and Richard Sackler
is now named

00:26.792 --> 00:28.542
president of Purdue Pharma.

00:28.542 --> 00:32.042
‐ Dr. Finnix, is this yours?
You're under arrest.

00:32.042 --> 00:33.500
How long you here for?

00:33.500 --> 00:34.583
‐ 90 days.

00:34.583 --> 00:36.875
You think you can
get me some pills?

00:36.875 --> 00:39.958
‐ What's your next move?
‐ Go back to the FDA

00:39.958 --> 00:41.875
to make another set of demands

00:41.875 --> 00:43.208
to restrict access
to this drug.

00:43.208 --> 00:45.417
‐ Can you think about
how what you're doing

00:45.417 --> 00:47.042
might be affecting me?

00:47.042 --> 00:48.417
‐ No, I can't. I'm sorry.

00:49.000 --> 00:51.208
This is how I grew up, Lucas.

00:51.208 --> 00:53.542
Watching my friends
die from drugs.

00:53.542 --> 00:55.000
If you continue on this path,

00:55.000 --> 00:57.250
you're going to end up
just like them.

02:02.750 --> 02:05.625
‐ Hughes. Mark Hughes.

02:06.667 --> 02:08.000
Corvelli, Josh.

03:00.542 --> 03:02.000
‐ My name is Jay McCloskey.

03:02.000 --> 03:04.792
I am the U.S. Attorney
for the State of Maine.

03:04.792 --> 03:07.292
I am here today because
rampant drug abuse

03:07.292 --> 03:09.250
has infiltrated
our great state.

03:10.375 --> 03:13.083
Dr. Richard?

03:13.083 --> 03:15.792
Sorry to disturb you at lunch,
but there's an urgent issue.

03:15.792 --> 03:18.000
‐ An 80 mg tablet of OxyContin

03:18.000 --> 03:21.333
sells on the street for $100.

03:21.333 --> 03:26.042
This diversion has created a
domino effect of related crime.

03:26.042 --> 03:27.833
As U.S. Attorney,
I will be sending letters

03:27.833 --> 03:29.417
to doctors across our state

03:29.417 --> 03:33.208
to alert them to
the grave dangers of OxyContin.

03:33.208 --> 03:34.500
Any questions?

03:34.500 --> 03:36.083
‐ It says that OxyContin

03:36.083 --> 03:37.875
is becoming the most
serious criminal problem‐‐

03:37.875 --> 03:39.875
‐ Yes, I know how to read.

03:44.042 --> 03:47.708
How many of these letters
were sent?

03:47.708 --> 03:49.625
‐ He sent one
to every single doctor

03:49.625 --> 03:51.625
in the entire state of Maine.

03:56.958 --> 03:58.208
I remember the day

03:58.208 --> 03:59.708
that I first decided
to get clean.

03:59.708 --> 04:05.042
Me and my buddy Josh, we had
this drug test coming up, um,

04:05.042 --> 04:07.625
which is not great news
for two addicts, you know.

04:07.625 --> 04:09.708
So we ran to our dealer
and we're like,

04:09.708 --> 04:12.708
"Hey, man,
you know, what can we do?"

04:12.708 --> 04:14.542
And he tells us,

04:14.542 --> 04:17.458
"If you drink bleach
on the day of your test,

04:17.458 --> 04:19.208
it cleans your blood."

04:19.208 --> 04:21.708
So, the day of the test
comes around,

04:21.708 --> 04:23.167
and we're in the back
of the car,

04:23.167 --> 04:26.417
and we got this industrial
strength container of bleach,

04:26.417 --> 04:28.208
and we drink.

04:28.208 --> 04:32.375
Except the bleach fucking
burns like hell going down,

04:32.375 --> 04:37.042
so immediately I'm gagging,
You know, I spit it everywhere.

04:37.042 --> 04:42.833
But Josh, man‐‐fucking Josh,
he‐‐he downs it.

04:50.292 --> 04:52.542
Uh, the day Josh died

04:52.542 --> 04:56.000
is the day I knew
I needed to get clean.

04:56.000 --> 04:59.750
Uh, a year ago today, actually.

05:02.750 --> 05:07.792
Um, I've been to rehab
three times now, but,

05:07.792 --> 05:09.667
God, I finally feel like

05:09.667 --> 05:12.375
it's starting to make sense,
you know?

05:12.375 --> 05:16.125
‐ My third time was when it
really started to make sense.

05:18.333 --> 05:20.292
‐ Thanks, Dirk.
It takes a lot of guts

05:20.292 --> 05:23.042
to admit that your life
has become unmanageable.

05:23.042 --> 05:25.167
And we got your back.

05:25.167 --> 05:27.167
‐ Thank you.

05:28.958 --> 05:31.375
‐ Samuel.

05:31.375 --> 05:33.083
It's your turn.

05:33.083 --> 05:35.042
Would you like to share
anything today?

05:35.042 --> 05:37.833
‐ Oh, uh,

05:37.833 --> 05:39.833
no, no.

05:43.208 --> 05:45.083
‐ Maybe tomorrow.

05:45.083 --> 05:47.208
‐ Yeah.

05:47.208 --> 05:48.958
‐ Ian.

05:48.958 --> 05:52.125
We haven't heard from you yet.

05:58.625 --> 06:01.333
‐ Hey.
‐ Hey, man. What's up?

06:01.333 --> 06:03.000
‐ I was thinking
about what y'all

06:03.000 --> 06:04.417
were talking about out there.

06:04.417 --> 06:08.458
H‐‐how many times
have y'all been to rehab?

06:08.458 --> 06:11.583
‐ This is my, uh, fourth time.

06:11.583 --> 06:13.875
‐ Fifth for me.

06:13.875 --> 06:16.542
‐ All of it here?
Same place?

06:16.542 --> 06:18.208
‐ Nah, I've been
to three other centers.

06:18.208 --> 06:19.500
I like this one the best.

06:19.500 --> 06:22.042
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ Yeah, me too.

06:22.042 --> 06:25.083
‐ I'm just‐‐I'm just worried,
you know?

06:25.083 --> 06:26.667
Worried maybe it doesn't work.

06:26.667 --> 06:30.042
‐ Hey, Samuel, this place
was amazing for my cousin.

06:30.042 --> 06:32.875
He hasn't had a drink
in nine years.

06:32.875 --> 06:37.000
‐ Look, man, it's either here,
jail, or the morgue.

06:39.833 --> 06:41.125
‐ Yeah.

06:41.125 --> 06:42.917
I feel ignored sometimes.

06:45.458 --> 06:48.792
It's, uh, not easy

06:48.792 --> 06:51.458
being with someone who's never

06:51.458 --> 06:53.833
really present with you.

06:53.833 --> 06:56.792
‐ I feel bad. I‐‐

06:56.792 --> 06:59.792
it's just‐‐it's hard for me to

06:59.792 --> 07:01.583
talk about things
that are not work‐related.

07:01.583 --> 07:02.792
‐ Yeah, she's obsessed
with work.

07:02.792 --> 07:04.250
‐ I'm not obsessed with work.
‐ You are.

07:04.250 --> 07:06.125
‐ I'm just trying to prevent
mass deaths from occurring

07:06.125 --> 07:07.417
across the country.
‐ I can't really compete with

07:07.417 --> 07:08.667
mass deaths
across the country.

07:08.667 --> 07:09.833
‐ I'm not asking you
to compete with that.

07:09.833 --> 07:10.917
I'm just asking you
to understand that

07:10.917 --> 07:12.750
I can't just turn that off.

07:14.333 --> 07:18.667
‐ But you may be causing
the death of your marriage.

07:20.083 --> 07:22.083
Do you see
Paul's point of view?

07:28.042 --> 07:29.875
‐ I don't want that. I‐‐

07:32.417 --> 07:33.625
I'm really trying.

07:33.625 --> 07:35.375
I'm right here.
‐ I'm right here.

07:35.375 --> 07:39.000
‐ I want this to work out.
‐ I do too.

07:46.292 --> 07:47.542
‐ Hello, everyone.

07:49.583 --> 07:52.750
I truly appreciate you all
meeting with me again.

07:52.750 --> 07:54.333
I, um,

07:54.333 --> 07:57.625
I know our last interaction
was less than ideal.

07:57.625 --> 07:59.708
But my therapist says

07:59.708 --> 08:01.333
it's never too late
to apologize.

08:01.333 --> 08:04.542
‐ Well, sounds like you have
a terrific therapist.

08:06.625 --> 08:10.167
‐ So I have brought
numerous articles

08:10.167 --> 08:14.917
from major publications
about the dangers of OxyContin

08:14.917 --> 08:18.333
that has put Purdue
on the defensive.

08:19.750 --> 08:21.250
Public pressure is building.

08:21.250 --> 08:25.542
‐ I have also seen several
articles about DEA overreach.

08:25.542 --> 08:28.083
‐ Yeah, well, those stories
were planted by Purdue.

08:28.083 --> 08:30.750
‐ Deputy Director Meyer,

08:30.750 --> 08:33.708
are you aware that
there are millions of people

08:33.708 --> 08:35.833
who swear by this medication?

08:39.042 --> 08:42.542
‐ There are just as many lives
that are being destroyed by it.

08:42.542 --> 08:44.792
And I'm not just talking
about the ones who have died,

08:44.792 --> 08:47.000
but the lives that they touch.

08:47.000 --> 08:49.500
Their friends, their family.

08:49.500 --> 08:53.542
Communities are being ravaged
by crime over this drug.

08:53.542 --> 08:57.333
Marriages and friendships
have ended

08:57.333 --> 09:01.375
because of a pill
that, in some instances,

09:01.375 --> 09:03.625
neither person
has ever even taken.

09:07.583 --> 09:10.167
‐ The FDA's position
on OxyContin

09:10.167 --> 09:12.708
is that it is safe
when used as directed.

09:12.708 --> 09:15.917
But we would take action
against it

09:15.917 --> 09:18.833
if the drug was shown to be
unsafe when used as prescribed.

09:18.833 --> 09:22.417
‐ But determining the safety
of the drug is the FDA's job.

09:22.417 --> 09:23.958
‐ And we have already
carried out our job

09:23.958 --> 09:25.667
during the approval process.
‐ Well, what if you were wrong?

09:25.667 --> 09:28.542
‐ Bridget.
‐ It's possible.

09:28.542 --> 09:30.875
‐ The FDA would admit
we were wrong,

09:30.875 --> 09:32.875
if that was proven
to be the case.

09:35.708 --> 09:38.792
‐ So if I were to prove
that OxyContin is dangerous

09:38.792 --> 09:42.375
when taken as prescribed,
then the FDA would act?

09:42.375 --> 09:45.625
‐ Absolutely. We don't want
anyone to get hurt.

09:45.625 --> 09:48.958
But we need proof that
the drug itself is defective

09:48.958 --> 09:50.125
if we are going
to take a drastic

09:50.125 --> 09:52.625
and restrictive action
against any drug,

09:52.625 --> 09:57.708
especially one that millions of
people have come to rely upon.

09:57.708 --> 10:00.375
How many are dying?
Who is dying?

10:00.375 --> 10:03.333
And how are they dying?

10:03.333 --> 10:04.667
This is what I want to know.

10:04.667 --> 10:07.375
‐ I'm sorry, what exactly
are you asking for?

10:07.375 --> 10:10.083
‐ I want you to pull together
all the data we have

10:10.083 --> 10:12.208
on overdose deaths
from OxyContin,

10:12.208 --> 10:15.458
and I want them organized
by state and region.

10:15.458 --> 10:19.375
‐ The DEA doesn't have
data on overdoses.

10:19.375 --> 10:21.292
‐ What do you mean‐‐you don't?
‐ No.

10:21.292 --> 10:22.875
That information
would be spread out

10:22.875 --> 10:25.083
across the country,
state‐by‐state,

10:25.083 --> 10:28.708
or even county‐by‐county,
patchwork of isolated reports.

10:28.708 --> 10:30.333
It would be incredibly
difficult to gather it all.

10:30.333 --> 10:32.333
‐ Well, I'm a very
difficult woman.

10:32.333 --> 10:34.000
Let's do it.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.375
‐ Are you joking?
‐ No, I'm not.

10:36.375 --> 10:38.000
I want to do
an exhaustive study

10:38.000 --> 10:41.417
on OxyContin overdose deaths,
and this is key‐‐

10:41.417 --> 10:43.583
I want to know
how many of those deaths

10:43.583 --> 10:45.708
are coming from people
who are taking the drug

10:45.708 --> 10:47.917
exactly as prescribed.

10:47.917 --> 10:51.375
Is that something you can
ascertain from the autopsy?

10:51.375 --> 10:53.375
‐ Potentially, yes, but,

10:53.375 --> 10:55.292
just to be clear,
so you understand

10:55.292 --> 10:57.125
exactly what you're asking for.
‐ Okay.

10:57.125 --> 10:58.250
‐ We're going to
have to go through

10:58.250 --> 11:00.125
thousands of autopsies
individually,

11:00.125 --> 11:01.708
match autopsies
with police reports,

11:01.708 --> 11:03.750
and dig through
handwritten notes.

11:03.750 --> 11:06.917
It will take
quite a bit of time.

11:06.917 --> 11:08.833
‐ I don't care
how much time it takes.

11:13.125 --> 11:14.375
Morning, Rick.

11:19.125 --> 11:21.542
Happy anniversary.

11:21.542 --> 11:23.292
We opened the case
three years ago.

11:23.292 --> 11:25.167
I was gonna get you
rhubarb pie,

11:25.167 --> 11:26.708
but the bakery was out.

11:26.708 --> 11:30.083
Feels like
a long three years.

11:30.083 --> 11:32.542
Still haven't even begun
to nail a top executive.

11:32.542 --> 11:34.125
‐ Come on, man.

11:34.125 --> 11:36.208
We were so close
to a whistleblower.

11:36.208 --> 11:37.875
And we're gonna
find another one.

11:37.875 --> 11:39.833
We're solid on misbranding.

11:39.833 --> 11:42.333
We can show the 1% claim
was fraudulent.

11:42.333 --> 11:44.083
So, I mean,
there's a lot here for a jury.

11:44.083 --> 11:45.250
‐ I'm not worried about a jury.

11:45.250 --> 11:48.625
I'm‐‐I'm worried
about Main Justice,

11:48.625 --> 11:51.708
because you know
who's gonna go out and lobby

11:51.708 --> 11:55.000
everyone he knows there,
and I just don't want

11:55.000 --> 11:58.625
this case to get
brushed under the rug.

11:58.625 --> 12:00.708
But if we start charging
individuals with felonies,

12:00.708 --> 12:03.667
we need the kill shot.

12:03.667 --> 12:06.458
‐ What was the name of that
U.S. Attorney up in Maine?

12:06.458 --> 12:08.000
‐ Jay McCloskey?

12:08.000 --> 12:09.667
‐ Did he dig
into Purdue at all?

12:09.667 --> 12:11.750
I think he had
a few meetings with them,

12:11.750 --> 12:13.625
but nothing significant
came from it.

12:13.625 --> 12:14.792
I'll reach out to him.

12:14.792 --> 12:17.625
I think
he's in private practice now.

12:17.625 --> 12:19.917
‐ We should look
into the doctors again.

12:19.917 --> 12:21.958
