was for you too,

17:10.208 --> 17:12.500
without you even knowing it.

17:12.500 --> 17:14.333
You've always been
near the Lord.

17:14.333 --> 17:16.333
He's always loved you.

17:20.292 --> 17:22.583
‐ Do you think
He can help me now?

17:22.583 --> 17:27.000
‐ Oh, yes. He can.

17:27.000 --> 17:28.958
But you have to accept Him
into your heart.

17:28.958 --> 17:30.667
And when you do,

17:30.667 --> 17:31.958
He'll guide you out
of this darkness.

17:31.958 --> 17:35.292
He'll cast that devil
right out of your soul.

17:35.292 --> 17:36.667
'Cause He loves you,
Betsy Mallum,

17:36.667 --> 17:39.125
and deep down inside,
you've always loved Him.

17:41.792 --> 17:43.583
‐ Maybe I‐‐maybe I have.

17:43.583 --> 17:45.167
Of course you have.

17:45.167 --> 17:48.625
That's what led you
to church every Sunday.

17:48.625 --> 17:52.958
And that love will lead you
to the path of recovery.

17:56.333 --> 17:59.292
Would you like to pray with me?

18:13.833 --> 18:16.917
I'm kind of worried,
to be honest with you.

18:16.917 --> 18:20.833
I mean, the recidivism rate is
awfully high in these places.

18:20.833 --> 18:23.333
People keep coming back.

18:23.333 --> 18:26.500
What if it just doesn't work?

18:28.500 --> 18:31.042
‐ I've been sober 14 years,
seven months,

18:31.042 --> 18:32.708
three weeks, two days.

18:32.708 --> 18:35.750
So many have been saved
by this program.

18:37.708 --> 18:40.417
‐ What were you addicted to?

18:40.417 --> 18:43.000
‐ I'm a recovering alcoholic.

18:43.000 --> 18:45.208
‐ Well, I'm on OxyContin.
Yeah?

18:45.208 --> 18:48.000
And this place‐‐

18:48.000 --> 18:50.708
this place used to be
90% alcohol and cocaine,

18:50.708 --> 18:55.042
and in the past two years,
it's 90% OxyContin.

18:55.042 --> 18:57.917
It's all addiction, Samuel.
‐ Yeah.

18:57.917 --> 19:00.208
It's all the same fight.

19:00.208 --> 19:02.042
‐ Okay.

19:02.042 --> 19:04.458
‐ I want to talk
about the early days,

19:04.458 --> 19:07.750
when you first
started prescribing.

19:07.750 --> 19:09.958
Did Purdue give you
any kickbacks?

19:09.958 --> 19:13.333
‐ Just the usual stuff.

19:13.333 --> 19:16.625
Expensive dinners,
tickets to football games.

19:16.625 --> 19:21.292
I went to a few of their
weekend seminars in Orlando.

19:21.292 --> 19:24.250
‐ Anything specific about
those weekends that you recall?

19:25.708 --> 19:28.167
‐ Pretty girls.

19:28.167 --> 19:30.458
Stuffed animals.

19:30.458 --> 19:35.042
They made a great case
for why the drug was so safe.

19:35.042 --> 19:37.583
‐ What did they say?

19:37.583 --> 19:40.000
‐ That it was
basically non‐addictive

19:40.000 --> 19:42.958
because
of its time‐release system.

19:42.958 --> 19:44.875
The FDA label
was a big part of it.

19:47.875 --> 19:50.458
And the blood charts.

19:50.458 --> 19:51.958
‐ Blood charts. So these‐‐

19:51.958 --> 19:54.250
these are the ones
that showed that the drug

19:54.250 --> 19:56.833
plateaued in the bloodstream
instead of spiked.

19:56.833 --> 19:58.667
‐ Yeah, those.

19:58.667 --> 20:00.000
‐ Explain those to me,
would you?

20:00.000 --> 20:02.542
'Cause I‐‐like,
I don't always get the science.

20:02.542 --> 20:06.375
‐ Charts show that the drug
remained smooth and even

20:06.375 --> 20:08.542
in the blood
because of the timed release,

20:08.542 --> 20:10.500
versus the drug spiking
up and down in the blood

20:10.500 --> 20:12.708
of an immediate‐release pill,
like Vicodin.

20:12.708 --> 20:14.000
‐ Mm.
This made the drug

20:14.000 --> 20:15.417
less prone to abuse,

20:15.417 --> 20:18.500
'cause it didn't give the user
a feeling of euphoria.

20:21.208 --> 20:23.750
‐ And you found that
these charts swayed you

20:23.750 --> 20:25.292
on the drug's safety.

20:25.292 --> 20:28.375
‐ Oh, definitely.

20:28.375 --> 20:30.500
It was the phrase they used.

20:30.500 --> 20:32.833
‐ Fewer peaks and valleys.

20:32.833 --> 20:36.583
‐ I hadn't heard that before,
and it felt safe.

20:40.208 --> 20:43.542
‐ But the drug is not safer.

20:46.875 --> 20:49.833
Then...

20:49.833 --> 20:53.125
wouldn't the charts...

20:53.125 --> 20:57.500
be false?

20:57.500 --> 21:01.542
‐ Yeah.

21:03.083 --> 21:05.208
You might be right.

21:05.208 --> 21:07.125
‐ Oh, this chart
is absolutely deceptive.

21:07.125 --> 21:08.750
See, right here.

21:08.750 --> 21:10.833
The Y‐axis is
on the logarithmic scale,

21:10.833 --> 21:13.625
not a linear one,
like most normal charts.

21:13.625 --> 21:16.000
So the top number is 100 mg.

21:16.000 --> 21:18.208
Now, on a normal linear scale,

21:18.208 --> 21:21.167
this number halfway down
would be 50.

21:21.167 --> 21:23.667
But see what Purdue did?

21:23.667 --> 21:26.667
They dramatically
compressed the scale.

21:26.667 --> 21:29.750
See here, from 10 to 50,

21:29.750 --> 21:32.625
and then from 50 to 100.

21:34.083 --> 21:35.792
‐ What does that mean?

21:35.792 --> 21:37.625
‐ It's been manipulated.

21:37.625 --> 21:40.667
The Purdue chart hides the fact
that OxyContin's blood levels

21:40.667 --> 21:42.667
actually drop precipitously
in the first few hours.

21:42.667 --> 21:44.708
If we look at
the non‐manipulated chart,

21:44.708 --> 21:45.833
we see how it should look.

21:45.833 --> 21:48.542
Even intervals
all the way up the axis,

21:48.542 --> 21:53.000
that shows spikes and drops,
like all opioids have.

21:53.000 --> 21:56.833
‐ So you're telling us that
these OxyContin blood charts,

21:56.833 --> 21:59.208
they deliberately
created a false impression.

21:59.208 --> 22:00.542
100%.

22:00.542 --> 22:02.625
This is a false plateau.

22:02.625 --> 22:04.625
And unless you're
a trained data scientist,

22:04.625 --> 22:06.833
you wouldn't catch it.

22:06.833 --> 22:10.208
What's really strange to me
is why the FDA approved it.

22:10.208 --> 22:11.917
‐ This would require
FDA approval?

22:11.917 --> 22:13.917
They approve all these charts.

22:13.917 --> 22:16.750
And there's no way they'd miss
the log scale manipulation.

22:16.750 --> 22:18.125
The only way this chart
makes it through

22:18.125 --> 22:22.875
the FDA approval process
is if they turned a blind eye.

22:27.833 --> 22:29.083
There is a deep connection

22:29.083 --> 22:31.458
between drugs and terrorism.

22:31.458 --> 22:33.458
It's history,

22:33.458 --> 22:35.875
but it also reflects
today's reality.

22:35.875 --> 22:38.833
And no one knows this more
than our guest of honor,

22:38.833 --> 22:40.417
Time Magazine's Man of the Year

22:40.417 --> 22:43.125
for his leadership
in the wake of 9/11,

22:43.125 --> 22:44.833
and my good friend,

22:44.833 --> 22:46.167
Mayor Rudy Giuliani.

22:50.417 --> 22:55.083
Thank you, Asa.
Thank you.

22:55.083 --> 22:57.583
Thank you, thank you.

22:57.583 --> 22:59.625
I'd like to thank those

22:59.625 --> 23:02.125
whose generosity
made this exhibit possible

23:02.125 --> 23:04.208
at the DEA Museum.

23:04.208 --> 23:06.542
Drug trafficking
funds terrorism.

23:06.542 --> 23:10.167
But beyond that,
they are both intended

23:10.167 --> 23:13.458
to break the spirit
of this great country.

23:13.458 --> 23:15.500
But that won't happen.

23:15.500 --> 23:18.500
Not with the hard work
of the DEA.

23:20.917 --> 23:24.042
Deputy Director Meyer, correct?

23:26.250 --> 23:28.875
‐ Yes, sir.
I'm sorry. I'm just‐‐

23:28.875 --> 23:31.333
it's such an honor to meet you.

23:31.333 --> 23:34.625
What you have done for
this country was unbelievable.

23:34.625 --> 23:36.792
‐ So important for all of us.
Thank you.

23:36.792 --> 23:38.583
‐ I lost two friends
in the South Tower.

23:38.583 --> 23:40.583
‐ I'm so sorry.

23:40.583 --> 23:44.500
I'm so sorry.
‐ Thank you.

23:44.500 --> 23:48.042
‐ But I have to say
the honor is mine.

23:48.042 --> 23:50.917
You are the highest‐ranking
woman in the DEA, correct?

23:50.917 --> 23:53.708
‐ Yes, sir.

23:53.708 --> 23:55.167
‐ I've heard really
great things about you,

23:55.167 --> 23:57.250
and I'd love to chat.

23:57.250 --> 23:58.625
‐ I would be honored. Any time.

23:58.625 --> 24:00.417
‐ How about right now?

24:00.417 --> 24:01.958
‐ Uh, sure.

24:01.958 --> 24:03.375
Great.

24:04.792 --> 24:09.292
You may not know this,
but I'm a cancer survivor.

24:09.292 --> 24:11.625
I did know.
And I am so sorry.

24:11.625 --> 24:13.375
Thank you so much.

24:13.375 --> 24:16.250
I got through it,
and because of my experience,

24:16.250 --> 24:19.042
I truly understand
the pain and distress

24:19.042 --> 24:20.875
that accompany illness.

24:20.875 --> 24:25.208
I just started a new firm,
and I had to really think hard

24:25.208 --> 24:27.333
about what kinds of cases
I would take on.

24:27.333 --> 24:29.042
And after what I went through,

24:29.042 --> 24:31.958
I felt like I was
in a unique position

24:31.958 --> 24:34.375
to represent Purdue Pharma.

24:34.375 --> 24:35.875
I'd love for you
to come to my office

24:35.875 --> 24:38.458
sometime in the next week
and see a presentation

24:38.458 --> 24:41.625
that I put together
on OxyContin.

24:41.625 --> 24:44.833
I think Purdue has

24:44.833 --> 24:46.625
a wonderful drug.

24:46.625 --> 24:49.042
And they're doing
all that they can

24:49.042 --> 24:52.208
to keep it
out of the wrong hands.

24:59.625 --> 25:00.750
‐ How much do you think

25:00.750 --> 25:02.833
Giuliani raised
for the DEA Museum?

25:02.833 --> 25:04.625
10 grand? 20?

25:04.625 --> 25:06.042
‐ Whatever it is,
it's not good.

25:06.042 --> 25:07.417
Yeah.
‐ And it's not good

25:07.417 --> 25:09.458
for your investigation.
This guy is a national hero.

25:09.458 --> 25:11.292
He's friends
with the president.

25:28.667 --> 25:30.917
‐ We finally heard
from Jay McCloskey,

25:30.917 --> 25:33.792
the U.S. Attorney in Maine.
‐ I know who he is.

25:37.208 --> 25:38.708
‐ Dr. Richard,

25:38.708 --> 25:40.875
you've become
very curt with me,

25:40.875 --> 25:43.958
and it's disrespectful.

25:45.125 --> 25:50.292
And frankly,
it's getting upsetting.

25:53.875 --> 25:55.583
‐ Jay McCloskey?

25:58.333 --> 26:00.875
‐ Yes.

26:00.875 --> 26:03.542
He's going to chair
a law enforcement conference

26:03.542 --> 26:08.000
on how to best deal with
the OxyContin issue.

26:08.000 --> 26:09.500
‐ That's good.

26:09.500 --> 26:10.750
‐ I agree.

26:10.750 --> 26:13.000
We need to keep this
a law enforcement issue

26:13.000 --> 26:14.542
and not a medical issue.

26:14.542 --> 26:18.042
He's‐‐he's invited us
to attend.

26:18.042 --> 26:20.208
And I think we should send
a small delegation

26:20.208 --> 26:22.917
to make clear we want to help
in any way we can.

26:22.917 --> 26:24.917
‐ Absolutely.

26:24.917 --> 26:27.875
We need him
to understand abusers

26:27.875 --> 26:30.792
are compromising life‐saving
medications.

26:30.792 --> 26:34.417
We need to keep
hammering the abusers.

26:41.875 --> 26:44.417
‐ You know,

26:44.417 --> 26:46.833
I actually think
you shouldn't attend.

26:49.292 --> 26:52.167
‐ Why not?

26:52.167 --> 26:55.542
‐ You have really passionate
feelings on addiction,

26:55.542 --> 26:58.458
and we need to be as politic
as possible right now,

26:58.458 --> 27:01.208
something that you, at times,

27:01.208 --> 27:04.542
are not very good at.

27:10.083 --> 27:12.083
‐ Hm.

27:26.208 --> 27:28.000
Fine.

27:32.417 --> 27:37.333
Just be sure
to hammer the abusers.

27:39.000 --> 27:44.167
I haven't shared
very much or spoken

27:44.167 --> 27:46.042
about anything in here, like‐‐

27:46.042 --> 27:49.208
like all‐‐all you guys did.

27:51.708 --> 27:56.125
So I want to‐‐
I want to apologize for that.

27:56.125 --> 27:58.125
I don't know
if all of you know this‐‐

27:58.125 --> 28:00.458
some of you might know‐‐
but I was a‐‐

28:00.458 --> 28:02.458
I was a physician

28:02.458 --> 28:06.375
who prescribed OxyContin

28:06.375 --> 28:09.542
to some of my patients.

28:09.542 --> 28:12.500
Some of these people,
I considered my friends.

28:15.750 --> 28:19.875
Some of them became addicted.

28:22.917 --> 28:25.917
Some of them died.

28:29.458 --> 28:32.458
Sometimes I think I'm the one
who should have died.

28:39.333 --> 28:42.208
These are just good,
decent people

28:42.208 --> 28:43.250
who thought
they could trust me,

28:43.250 --> 28:44.500
and I feel like
I betrayed them,

28:44.500 --> 28:47.708
and I feel like
I let them down.

28:53.292 --> 28:56.292
I'm just gonna have
to live with that.

29:01.875 --> 29:03.750
I don't even know if I'm ready

29:03.750 --> 29:05.625
to go out into the world,
but...

29:07.583 --> 29:10.792
Well, there you go.

29:11.417 --> 29:14.417
Guess I'll give it a shot.

29:16.792 --> 29:19.833
I don't know, I feel, uh,

29:19.833 --> 29:21.333
like I'm still addicted,
you know?

29:21.333 --> 29:24.125
Like‐‐like I still need it.

29:24.125 --> 29:27.125
Well, these feelings
don't magically go away.

29:27.125 --> 29:29.708
It's gonna feel
overwhelming at times.

29:29.708 --> 29:32.875
But it is important
to live one day at a time.

29:32.875 --> 29:33.875
You know?
‐ Yeah.

29:33.875 --> 29:37.083
‐ Wake up each morning,

29:37.083 --> 29:39.292
recommit to the process.

29:39.292 --> 29:41.708
‐ Okay. Well...

29:42.958 --> 29:44.792
‐ You have someone
picking you up?

29:44.792 --> 29:45.917
‐ Yeah.
‐ Good.

29:45.917 --> 29:48.500
‐ Yeah, I'll just wait here.
I do.

29:48.500 --> 29:50.625
‐ Hey.

29:50.625 --> 29:51.792
We're here if you need us.

29:51.792 --> 29:52.833
‐ Okay, thank you.

29:52.833 --> 29:54.417
‐ All right.

30:43.208 --> 30:47.333
Dear Lord, thank you
for this glorious meal.

30:47.333 --> 30:52.542
For my health,
my‐‐my recovery.

30:52.542 --> 30:55.333
But most of all,

30:55.333 --> 30:59.958
I want to thank you
for my wonderful parents,

30:59.958 --> 31:04.542
who have stuck with me through
the most horrible of times.

31:04.542 --> 31:08.125
I'm so lucky to have them.

31:08.125 --> 31:11.500
And to have you in my life,
dear Lord.

31:14.875 --> 31:17.208
I know I wouldn't make it
without you all here

31:17.208 --> 31:21.542
to protect me.

31:21.542 --> 31:23.042
Amen.

31:23.042 --> 31:26.375
‐ Amen.
‐ Amen.

31:26.375 --> 31:29.125
Bets, if you come away
from this

31:29.125 --> 31:31.792
with a greater love
of the Lord,

31:31.792 --> 31:34.333
I promise you
it'll be worth it.

31:36.167 --> 31:38.667
‐ I think so too.

32:03.750 --> 32:05.625
Dr. Finnix?

32:07.792 --> 32:09.417
Dr. Finnix.

32:12.333 --> 32:14.417
Dr. Finnix!

32:16.875 --> 32:20.500
Dr. Finnix?

32:20.500 --> 32:22.958
‐ One second.

32:24.792 --> 32:26.917
Hey.

32:26.917 --> 32:29.167
Hey, how you doing?

32:29.167 --> 32:31.500
‐ Are you joking?
You called me last night

32:31.500 --> 32:33.083
and said you were gonna
kill yourself.

32:35.542 --> 32:38.250
‐ I did?

32:38.250 --> 32:41.958
No, that's‐‐

32:41.958 --> 32:44.750
I wasn't serious.

32:46.875 --> 32:49.375
‐ Are you gonna invite me in?

32:49.375 --> 32:51.917
Yeah, please, come in.

32:51.917 --> 32:55.375
‐ I was on the night shift,
so I couldn't leave.

32:55.375 --> 32:57.292
I was worried sick about you.

33:00.375 --> 33:02.833
‐ Sit. Come on, sit down.

33:02.833 --> 33:06.208
How you doing? How you doing?

33:06.208 --> 33:07.833
You want some coffee
or something?

33:07.833 --> 33:09.917
‐ No. Thank you.

33:09.917 --> 33:12.500
‐ You want some juice?

33:12.500 --> 33:15.000
‐ You're using again,
aren't you?

33:18.208 --> 33:19.792
‐ Yeah.

33:27.833 --> 33:30.667
You know, rehab didn't work.

33:30.667 --> 33:32.250
I mean, you know,

33:32.250 --> 33:34.375
people over there
just keeps coming in and out,

33:34.375 --> 33:35.625
going back and forth.

33:35.625 --> 33:38.917
They come in, they go out,
they come in.

33:38.917 --> 33:42.208
‐ A doctor at the hospital
told me the same thing.

33:42.208 --> 33:44.875
He said those places
work better for alcohol.

33:44.875 --> 33:49.375
That recovery is a lot harder
for opiates.

33:49.375 --> 33:52.583
‐ It's damn near impossible.

33:55.500 --> 33:57.792
‐ Have you thought
about methadone?

33:57.792 --> 33:59.708
He said it might work.

33:59.708 --> 34:01.917
‐ Just get addicted, like,
trade one for the other one,

34:01.917 --> 34:05.542
'cause those guys‐‐
those Vietnam guys‐‐

34:07.667 --> 34:09.208
the vets I used to work with,

34:09.208 --> 34:11.250
they just called it
liquid handcuffs,

34:11.250 --> 34:14.458
'cause you just‐‐
you know, just‐‐same thing.

34:14.458 --> 34:16.792
Well, you gotta try something.

34:16.792 --> 34:18.375
‐ Yeah.

34:19.708 --> 34:23.583
‐ I asked around, and there's
a good clinic in Knoxville.

34:23.583 --> 34:25.958
It's worth a shot, Dr. Finnix.

34:28.167 --> 34:30.750
‐ I'm not a doctor anymore.

34:30.750 --> 34:32.792
‐ I don't care what you are.

34:32.792 --> 34:36.208
I just don't want you dead.

34:36.208 --> 34:38.750
Can't you at least try it?

34:51.125 --> 34:54.208
I'm sorry, we have
to postpone St. Moritz.

34:54.208 --> 34:57.250
‐ But the kids are really
looking forward to it.

34:57.250 --> 35:00.042
I mean, David won't shut up
about those new skis.

35:00.042 --> 35:01.708
It's‐‐it's only two weekdays.

35:01.708 --> 35:03.208
‐ It's a very serious
situation.

35:03.208 --> 35:04.458
A U.S. Attorney in Maine

35:04.458 --> 35:06.208
is causing
some real problems for us.

35:08.667 --> 35:10.417
‐ What are you so afraid of?

35:10.417 --> 35:11.750
You're president.

35:11.750 --> 35:16.542
The drug is making
a billion a year.

35:16.542 --> 35:18.500
Why can't you just enjoy it?

35:22.375 --> 35:24.833
‐ Maybe I'm not capable of joy.

35:32.208 --> 35:34.792
‐ Then the kids and I
will go without you.

35:37.250 --> 35:38.833
‐ Okay.

35:54.500 --> 35:55.833
Well, thanks
for meeting with us.

35:55.833 --> 35:58.042
I know the FDA must be
pretty overwhelmed

35:58.042 --> 36:01.125
with approvals and such.

36:01.125 --> 36:04.000
‐ We are.
How can I help you?

36:04.000 --> 36:07.583
‐ We want to know
how the approval process works

36:07.583 --> 36:09.500
for scientific charts.

36:12.750 --> 36:14.917
‐ Well, any data
that a company wants to use

36:14.917 --> 36:17.625
in marketing and promotions

36:17.625 --> 36:22.458
has to be approved by us,
to ensure accuracy.

36:22.458 --> 36:27.125
‐ So if Purdue Pharma used
specific language in charts,

36:27.125 --> 36:29.875
then the FDA approved it?

36:29.875 --> 36:32.167
‐ That's correct.

36:32.167 --> 36:34.208
‐ We'd like to ask you

36:34.208 --> 36:36.458
about this blood chart
that sales reps at Purdue

36:36.458 --> 36:38.667
showed doctors to demonstrate
that the drug

36:38.667 --> 36:42.000
didn't have the same peaks
and valleys as other opiates.

36:48.125 --> 36:49.708
Would you guys give us
the room for a minute?

36:49.708 --> 36:52.208
- Sure.
- Thank you.

37:01.375 --> 37:04.375
Where did you get this?
‐ In discovery, at Purdue.

37:05.958 --> 37:08.958
‐ And you're sure that

37:08.958 --> 37:12.333
this is a chart that Purdue
reps actually showed doctors?

37:12.333 --> 37:13.917
‐ Mm‐hmm. A version of it.

37:13.917 --> 37:15.333
There are others
that are similar.

37:15.333 --> 37:19.583
‐ It was used in seminars
and for promotional purposes.

37:19.583 --> 37:21.125
‐ God damn it.

37:23.542 --> 37:26.667
